**TCP/IP PROTOCOL SUITE : **
internet protocol suite, actual real world conceptal model and set of communication protocosl used to power the modern internet and all ip based networks, while OSI MODEL is an abstract framework with 7 layers, tcp/ip suite is a lean, 4 layer architecture designed for practical implementation, every time borwser opened, stream a video or query a remote nosql datastore, data passes through specific stack

4 layers of tcp/ip suite: 
- application layer : combines the functions of the OSI model's top three layers (application presentation and session), provides direct network services to user apps and handles data formatting, encryption and session initialization
              - core protocols : http/https for loading web pages, DNS (translates human readable domain names into numeric IP addresses, ssh/ftp for secure remote access and file movement
- transport layer : manages host to host data delivery, ensuring data chunks get to the correct software app on the receivign device, slices data into segments and manages traffic speeds
              - TCP (transmission control protocol) : a connection oriented protocol that guarantees delivery, uses  sequence numbers and a "three way handshake" to ensure no packets are lost or corrupted
              - UDP (user datagram protocol) : a connectionless, rapid fire protocol, it drops error checking and verification to favor raw speed, making it perrfect for live video streaming and gaming
- Internet layer : handles the addressing packaging and routing of **data packets** across multiple independt networks, layer gives rhe suite its global reach, 
              - IP (internet protocol -IPv4, IPv6) responsible for logically addressing data packets so routers know exactly where to send them
              - ICMP : used for network diagnostics 

- Network Access Layer (Link Layer) : combines the OSI Model's bottom two layers (data link and physical), dictates how data is physically framed and transmitted over a specific hardware medium as bits (elctric, radio ro light isgnlas),
            - core protocols : **ethernet, 802.11(wifi) and point to point protocol (PPP)**

Real world execution : when nosql db replicates data to another server accross country: 
  - db app hands the write update to the app layer, 
  - trnsport layer uses tcp to guarantee that not a single byte of that db record gets corrupted during the journey
  - intenret layer tsamsp the Ip address of the destination replica server on the data packets
  - network access layer translates those packets into physical ligth flashes through a fiber optic cable link to cross the country





**DIFF BETWEEN TCP/IP AND OSI MODEL : **
whille both are conceptual frameworks used to understand how computer networks operae, OSI model is an acadmeic, theoritical blueprint, whereas the tcoip model is aptractical, real world architcetrue thta actually powers the modern internet


OSI : 
created by ISO as atherotical guide, was designed before its specific protocols were invented, making it highly structured but less practical for immediate real world use

uses strict, granular 7 layer architecture, treats data formatting, session management and app interaction as completely diff tasks

supports both connectionlewss and connection oriented comm at network layer, but strictly connection oriented communication at the trasnport layer

TCP/IP : 
devved by US dept of defense, in 1970s, fro ARPANET, tcp and ip protocols were designed and implemented forst, then the model was built around them based on what actually worked

uses a streamlined 4 layer architecture, combines overlapping functionalities to reduce complexity

supports only connectionless cumm at the internet layer (ip simply routes packets without checking if the receiver is ready), but gives developers a choice between connection oriented (tcp) or connectionless (UDP) at the transport layer

